,Recommended,245170,34954972,Posted: 14 September,all,ｘｍｏｓｐｈｅｒｅ,"With Dragonball FighterZ on the way and Marvel vs Capcom Infinite coming out in a few days. I wanted to take the time to reflect on one of the better 3v3 fighters out there. Skullgirls offers both a suprising depth and accessibility to people who have never played either a fighting game or a 3v3 fighting game. For me, this was the first fighting game I got into after seeing a video on it. I was impressed by how well animated the sprites were. The first thing I tell people who want to learn fighting games is to buy this and play the tutorial. Unlike other fighting games with as the street fighter series, Skullgirls tutorial offers a look into important concepts. For example there is a part of the tutorial for both how to do mix ups, practice blocking mix ups, and where mix ups are not safe on block and can be punished. The gameplay on the other hand is different. While not revolutionary like the tutorial system, it offers a robust mechanically deep gameplay. The netcode is also phenomenal allowing to set the amount of buffer frames. The 2 downsides to online play is that in my experience it takes forever to get a match and if you are a beginner you are going to get your♥♥♥♥♥handed to you by people who know every reset within a combo and how to extend a combo to avoid the anti infinite system for as long as possible.EDIT: Apparently the netcode is rollback not frame delay. It uses GGPO netcode so its not the same as SFV's rollback netcode."
,Recommended,245170,10155312,"Posted: 17 May, 2014",all,agares,"Finally another fighting game for the pc that is very well done, let's go by parts. Graphics, the game looks beautiful, all characters well done with details on every corner, the sprites are great, and the sprite of a fallen character can even be different depending on what kind of attack the character received before going down, the backgrounds are also well done, with lots of details everywhere, and the artwork is completely hand-drawn, and it's really not bad. Sound, the voice acting is very well selected for each character, there was one which I personally found kinda off before, Painwheel's, but now I see why it was chosen, the music very well done, each one sounding unique. Gameplay, the game runs 60 frames per second, completely smooth, all characters have different playstyles and feel pretty unique (Fukua is a clone character, she was made as an Aprill fools joke, as a parody of Decapre from Ultra Super Street Fighter IV, she was avaible only at the endless beta, but now she's a hidden character by she side of Big Band in the final game.). The game has almost no delay when the player presses a button, and it even has an anti infinite combo system. The game has local and online multiplayer, and the online multiplayer is very good, with a great connection, the player can create lobbies, with the maximum of 6 players, but the game itself might not be the easiest game for a begginer at fighting games, but the game has a very good tutorial mode, with even tutorials for learning how to use the characters, and the final boss is.... Very cheap to say the least, but certainly a challenge, and this game also has a gigantic number of references on it. At the moment all the DLC characters are not out yet, which when they are, they stay free for a limited number of time, so the player can decide if it's worth to buy the DLC or not, so when a new character is out, I'll test them, and if necessary, mention any change of anything at all, I will edit this review. I give this game a 9.5/10.0 a must-buy for fighting game fans."
