,Recommended,245170,12338211,"Posted: 3 October, 2014",all,Kasdiel,"Let me preface this by saying that Skullgirls isn't for everyone. If you don't like arcade fighting games, well, you probably won't like Skullgirls.That being said, if you do like the arcade fighting genre in the slightest this is a must-buy game.  Mechanically the game is among the best as far as fighters go but it's the memorable characters, beautiful artstyle and the imaginitive world on top of the extremely polished gameplay that take this game from being 'great' to being 'absolutely amazing.'Skullgirls is great for beginners looking to get into the genre as well, offering an extensive tutorial mode that covers the basics all the way up to mechanically-demanding mixups. (Combos that are unpredictable) Sure, tutorials are common in fighting games, however, the sheer depth of Skullgirls' tutorial is what makes it deserving of praise.Mechanically each of the characters are as diverse as their personalities. Through the tutorial you'll learn each character's role and weaknesses and as new characters are added they're given lessons in the tutorial as well, giving all the more reason to endlessly praise Skullgirls' tutorial.The roster, although seemingly tiny, is being rounded out by additionally characters being added in future patches. At the time of writing this, three of those characters have been released with the remaining two being actively developed which round out the diverse roster of characters beautifully.That being said, the game is constantly being updated and patched with no sign of the developer stopping any time soon.The game is fanservice-y, yes. Is it tasteful? Honestly, yes, it's appropriate in the context of the game and the characterswithin it. If you can't handle female characters in sexualized outfits/poses then I don't know how you've played any other fighting game to be honest. The problem isn't that the characters are designed this way, it's that you have overly selective eyes and an extremely closed mind.So here’s where we’re at when all is said and done: we have a fighting game set in a gloriously original world, racked out with unique characters whose hand drawn animations are stunningly detailed. The soundtrack of the game is – at least for jazz fans – beautiful enough to warrant an OST purchase all on its own. The graphical presentation is phenomenal, the story mode is entertaining, the characters are unique and engaging as a whole. For fans of this genre do yourself a favor and purchase this game. At the $14.99 price point it's a steal as it's worth double that at the very least."
