,Recommended,245170,4306257,"Posted: 22 August, 2013",all,DudeDesigns,"*Original Review: Launch 2013Sub-Par street fighter clone with some good art.Community is absolutey♥♥♥♥♥ Good luck trying to find a semi-friendly person online or on the forums, because it'll take you days.Loved the game 2 years when it came out but agonizingly long updates made me lose interest. Ultimately it just makes you want to play an AAA fighting game, probably Street Fighter.The story modes don't have voice acting, there is no coherent story line anyway, it controls well I must say, but other than that there's not much to keep you tied to this game. If anything, SkullGirls was nothing but a platform for half decent porn amongst the internet and some ♥♥♥♥♥♥ rpg game being made by the communityIf mike z had made this an interactive dating simulator, he would have had enough money at the end of the first month of this game's life to make more than 6 dlc characters in its first ♥♥♥♥ing year than take 2+years for them.*Update 28/07/2016Skullgirls was released in 2012 for Xbox Live and Playstation Network for both Xbox360 and PS3. When the game launched, I supported this game with all my breath. Its a fast, fluid, and easy to pick up fighting game with gorgeous art and a kick♥♥♥♥♥soundtrack by Michiru Yamane. However, as the years went on, the community for this game made me put it down, time after time again. The game was Re-released on PS3 and Xbox Live as Skullgirls: Encore, and then RE-Re-released on PS4 as Skullgirls: 2nd Encore, which basically just added a voiced story mode, an art gallery, and a challenge mode, which have all found their way into the PC release by now.What made this game's community more toxic than some of the other fighting game communites (I'm looking at you SF IV, DoA V, and MK9), was the endless amount of drama on the SkullHeart forums, on the Steam Discussions, and on Steam Groups. Fighting games as a WHOLE have always had some of the worst gaming communites I've ever seen because everyone becomes so hyper-competitive that no one had fun. It got to the point where simply asking for a match got people to send you death threats on the forums. I used to stream this game every weekend back in 2013 through 2014. I met some friendly randoms, but about 85% of my matches consisted of people complaining about my fight style, saying I used cheap character combinations, etc etc.Now every game community in the world has players like this, but with SkullGirls, for the first 3 years of it life, it was literally nothing but♥♥♥♥♥♥posting, drama, and angry nig-nogs that couldn't stand losing in a video game. I've been called plenty of names on FPS games, I've had plenty of death threats from RTS', and of course, other fighting games, but SkullGirls took far too long to build a decent community that I just couldn't support it anymore. It doesn't help that Lead Desginer, Mike Z, is a savage GinoJew that banned people all the time from SkullHeart simply for having different opinionsSkullGirls is a completely enjoyable game, do not get me wrong, that's why I still recommend it. Over the years, the community has gotten far better than what it was 3 - 2 years ago, but it's still pretty ♥♥♥♥♥♥. If anything, you should buy this game to support the games main artist, Alex Ahad. He's a pretty good guy."
