,Recommended,245170,9675056,"Posted: 30 March, 2014",all,♠,"Skullgirls is an indie, 2d fighting game with the most lovely animations and characters ever, plus great gameplay. Some people came for nostalgia, some people came for the girls, but everyone stayed thanks to the amazing fighting gameplay it offers.- Characters and StoryBelieve it or not, this is a big part of the game actually - i have never played a fighting game with such likeable roster and interesting story. I expected the classic cutscenes where the character just ""wants to be the best fighter ever!"" and boy, i was wrong.  I started the game playing mostly with Valentine (the sexy nurse ninja) and Cerebella (Circus superstar with Vice-Versa, a hat with two superstrong arms) and their stories are already engaging (at least for a fighting game), but the most fun i've had was with Peacock. Her story mode was an emotional roller-coaster, oscillating between hilarious scenes that had me laughing out loud and moments that had me almost crying. While other fighting games have a bland roster with no personality (sometimes characters are just a recolor of others), in Skullgirls i can see that every character had a lot of love put on them during development. They're fleshed out, they're lovely, they're great.My only complaint: The roster could be bigger. But hey, it's an indie game, so i'll let that pass.- Gameplay (The Part that Really Matters)It's perfect. That's just how i can sum this up. Responsive, fast-paced, varied and very fun. If you like fighting games, this is right up your alley - it reminded me a lot of Guilty Gear and Marvel VS Capcom games, with aerial combos, several flashy ultra attacks for every character, insane combos and switching between characters of your team mid-fight. With a twist - you don't necessarily have to play a team, you can play with a single character or two high-powered characters instead of a crew of 3, if you want to sacrifice versatility in exchange for more power for your favorite character. Oh, and another fun addition - You know in Marvel vs Capcom when you were about to defeat one of the enemy's teammates and he switched? So, in Skullgirls you can punch out one of his characters and force another one to come back, at the cost of 1 level of your Blockbuster (special moves). Neat idea right? Another thing i loved is how several of the characters play in a really interesting way. I expected fighting game tropes (the ryu clone, the combo guy, etc) that every fighting game is plagued with, but every character in Skullgirls fights in their unique way. Some of them may remind you of someone else (Like Parasoul reminds me of Testament from GG), but they always have their own, original traits and twists.- Audio and VisualsFlawless! I love it! The soundtrack does not disappoint, fitting the stage and gameplay (i especially love theTraining Room tune), and the character's voices really impressed me. There is a very wide array of lines for every character, making sure they don't repeat the same sentence even when you repeat the same attack, and they call each other's names when switching teammates mid-fight, they have several unique lines to greet every specific character AND for their victory animations. Usually in fighting games the audio gets a bit repetitive after a while, but this is not the case. I actually still hear new lines whenever i play.And the visuals? Oh man. Maybe this games' biggest selling point? The hand-drawn, high-framerate animations are absolutely amazing. Reminds me of Darkstalkers actually - the likeable characters and excellent animations. Again, when i played with Valentine and Cerebella i was already impressed, but the highest point so far was Peacock ; she's downright hilarious when fighting, following that classic Disney animation style, very cartoony and fun. I think the visuals, together with the gameplay, are the best parts of this game - and they should be, that's exactly what matters in a fighting game.My only complaint: Every character has just one victory animation. (and one for time-out). Although they're not sooo repetitive since they have several lines to say, i wouldn't complain if we got more.- So, Should i Buy this Game? (TL;DR)Do you like fighting games? If you do, YES. Buy Skullgirls and you will not be disappointed.You don't like fighting games? Well, you're about to. Skullgirls will get you in the genre, guaranteed. I actually suck at fighting games (my specialty is shooters), and this game entertained me a lot. It's worth your money and more - I actually regret buying it on a sale, they deserved more money from me."
