76561198062481627,Recommended,245170,30919145,Posted: 3 April,all,ScolioReset,"There was a time where you had to go watch videos in order to learn fighting games. Somehow, Lab Zero (or all studios involved in the making of the game) decided to take the ""here's our Training Room, deal with it"" style of welcoming new players to the genre.Skullgirls features one of the best tutorials for any fighting game to date. In fact, it is the pioneer when it comes to actual excellent training modes, something that is included in Killer Instinct and Guilty Gear Xrd. If you find Street Fighter, Injustice or Mortal Kombat a little too intimidating or don't own an Xbox One or Windows 10, Skullgirls is a perfect alternative to Killer Instinct for newcomers to the genre. You basically learn the ropes of the genre by discovering terms like mix-ups, tick throws and all that kind of stuff. The game does let you learn the little details and nuances by doing the practices as much as you want with its incredible selection of lessons from movement to defense before going into offense.You can even set the Training Room in order to learn the hitboxes, frame data and combos. The Tutorial also allows you to learn character-specific movesets, technically special moves, for the content that you own. If you ever see this game on sale, you owe it to yourself to give it a shot. Maybe you'll discover why fighting games are more nuanced than they look. Maybe this will be the game that will make you good at it... like actually good instead of just pressing buttons.At a sale, the Training Mode is worth its asking price alone. The character designs and animations are great as well, Ms. Fortune being my favorite for some reason. And the soundtrack is wonderful! Skullgirls will give you the tools right off the bat and probably make you a slightly more experienced fighthing game player unlike others who are stepping into the genre by playing the more-known-yet-not-great-at-teaching titles."
