,Recommended,245170,14385745,"Posted: 8 February, 2015",all,devlkore,"My review is going to focus on the mechanics of the game but let me say this game has everything:- The story, presentation, graphics and audio create a wonderful universe.- The interactive tutorials teach you about the characters, game systems and fighting games as a whole (mix ups, hit confirms, etc.)- Best tools in practice mode of any fighting game I know of (I've played A LOT), including hitbox and hitstun display, slow motion, 'as reversal' dummy playback, savestates and more.- GGPO netcode.On to the actual fighting. Skullgirls can be played with mixed solo characters and teams of 2 or 3. Health, damage and defense are scaled so it's balanced. I prefer teams of 2 and occasionally 3, but a solo character can overwhelm a team if they get the momentum. Teams have assists and tagging similar to Marvel, though you can use any normal/special/throw attack as an assistant and all characters have unique tag in attacks.I really like the amount you can customise your team. It definitely helps offset what some might see as a limited roster of characters.Speaking of characters current cast of 12 (eventually to be 14) are all very unique and represent a wide variety of styles. My favourites are Big Band, the slow armour character that can actually play music (also he can parry), Cerebella, the grappler that also glides and can reflect projectiles, Valentine, because she's a ninja and can move wherever she wants and Eliza, the ""stand"" character. There's also a Scorpion/Angel hybrid stance character, a John Talbain pro wrestler, a dismembered cat girl with rekkas (and is also a doll character) and Fukua, the joke character that has a dragon kick so win all round.All characters have special moves and supers, for the most part very much like Street Fighter moves. Supers use 2 buttons rather than double motions. If playing with a team you can tag mid super into the next characters super. There is however no ability to perform multiple simultaneous super moves.Combos are largely formed out of chains, going in traditional ""magic series"", though there are links and plenty of unique chains. The combo system is very free form, the limiting factors are the infinite prevention system (IPS) and drama/undizzy bar. These limits are a good thing, they keep you from repeating the same thing over and over, keeping combos interesting and stopping any single combo from going on for too long. There are still high damage combos but you can't just loop something until timeout or death.If a combo starts to loop the player getting hit can burst out for free. This means you have to either end your combo or try to reset the other player into another combo, or even bait the burst and attack after.There are many unique character specific systems that make the game interesting and give the characters more depth. Big Band can parry attacks, Squigly can cancel normal attacks and move the screen around, Valentine can inflict 3 status effects and resurrect dead teammates, Painwheel can fly and absorb then reflect damage, and so many others.Character diversity is definitely one of the games strong points.So in summary, I highly recommend this game to anyone who loves 2D fighting games or would like to start playing them and to anyone who likes fighting games and appreciates the story and art. If I had to put a number on it I'd say 5/5, it's ""perfect"", everything it sets out to do it does beyond expected of a fighting game."
