76561198138745733,Recommended,245170,16747513,"Posted: 27 June, 2015",all,Giga Bill Breaker,"Skullgirls borrows mechanics from some of the most well known fighting games out there (King of Fighters, Marvel, Guilty Gear, Street Fighter, etc) and fuses them into a very solid and accessible little package.I cannot emphazise it enough, the game is very, very accessible. The control scheme is a 6 button layout, something with which almost everybody should be familiar with by now. However, for the execution of supers, you will be hard pressed to find moves that uses anything other than quarter circle motions (exception being the obligatory charge characters and DP motions).Blockbusters (flashy meter-dependent moves) even use the same motions, only requiring the press of two punches/kicks at the same time, reminding me of good old Darkstalkers.Every character has something to offer for people who are already used to certain archetypes, but puts a small spin on them.Wanna play as the usual Ryu clone? We have one, sans projectiles! Kind of...Wanna play the rushdown character who is fast as the wind? We have one! And she can throw her head at you...Wanna play a hit-hard but slow character? We have a Juggernaut/Iron Tager fusion!The game is also full to the brim with Tutorials, which range from ""How do I walk?"" to character specific moves and the many many many mechanics of the game (pushblocking, infintes prevention, overheads, all that jazz). These tutorials are very clear and easy to understand, and only a few mechanics might get you stuck for a few minutes.However, when I say this game is accessible, I don't mean this game can't have high level play. Quite the opposite.Every character has some kinks here and there that makes them viable in more ways than one, and you won't see 2 people play the same character the same way. The combo system is rather flexible, after all. Even if the tutorials teach you usual Bread n Butters and strategies for everyone, you can always think a bit and come up with something of your own.The other aspects of the game are also top notch. The music and animation are really great, and the story modes for each character range from ""that was pretty cool"" to ""OH GOG DID THAT JUST HAPPEN"".The only gripes people might have with this game might be the disappointing final boss (just a projectile factory at first, tho not as bad as Magaki) and the amount of DLC characters (which go rather cheap, and even cheaper during sales, so no biggie).The online play also has a few hiccups here and there, but if you stick to playing with people from your same continent you should be fine."
76561198046744787,Recommended,245170,14718308,"Posted: 1 March, 2015",all,Nerfthegamer,its good
,Recommended,245170,16588574,"Posted: 21 June, 2015",all,anditeo_t,"This game is incredible. I felt that it was incredibly easy to get into and learn, but has a lot of keep coming back to, as you will always get better as you play. The art is beautiful, and the combat is smooth and exciting. I can wholly recommend this to almost anyone that is a fan of the 2-D fighter genre."
