76561198008180658,Recommended,245170,16633756,"Posted: 22 June, 2015",all,Mokoma,"Skullgirls is a unique game. I never really played a fighting game on my computer, I did play some well-known fighting games on consoles, but if I had to be fair these experiences were sort of easy to forget. Skullgirls just had the charm that the other fighting games I played hadn't.In terms of mechanics, Skullgirls is very fluid. I'm not really a good-enough player to be launching precise strikes and combos on my opponent, but I truly felt that the game had a good sense of collision, and this is hard to pull off with a 2D game. The combat also does well with its fighters; every fighter is unique and has their own unique style of fighting. You'll find that playing Peacock, as her tutorial suggests, is truly better to play with ranged attacks, while Ms. Fortune's speciality is being able to detach her head and use it to make special attacks while her body is in an entirely different location. I don't have the hang of all the fighters just yet, but I managed to beat Marie on the first try with Ms. Fortune and on the second try with Peacock on Normal difficulty, in my book I think these two characters I've gotten more familiar with. My point is, all characters are different and suit different players, which is definitely a good thing. No character plays the same, and rarely would they have similar types of attacks.But to admit, the game caught my attention more through its characters, stories, appearances, and the blend of emotions I get to feel; one character's story is going to be full of humorous points, while the other could be just tearjerking, sometimes the two even blend into one. Interestingly enough, there's a lot of story that's hard to find out through playing the game alone, which is something I aim to expand my knowledge on past the writing of this review.What makes Skullgirls, in my opinion, better than any fighting game I've played so far?The combat is fluid, but at the same time it's unique. It's loose! There are a lot of various attacks (And don't get me started on how various Peacock's are), and it's playable. The game itself doesn't try to be edgy or anything, rather it has different fighters that give different sorts of feelings. Sexiness? Go for Valentine. Goofiness? Use Peacock. Adorableness? Squigly's the one for you. Anger? Painwheel. Horrible? That would be Double. There aren't many fighters just yet (As there is always potential and room for more), but that compensates for their good variability, appearance, and absolutely great voice acting.And who could forget about the game's non-mechanical aspects? The game is very visually beautiful, it's drawn well and animated with skill, the soundtrack is something I've already put on my MP3 playlist, and the character designs make the game remarkable in that aspect.I'll conclude by saying that as much as I lack experience, I love this game."
