76561198078679059,Recommended,245170,28353371,"Posted: 13 December, 2016",all,pb without the j,"Gaming has always been a thing my entire life. I grew up with the PlayStation 2 and the few games I had on the many computers I managed to get my hands on in my life before the discovery of got me to where I am today. I manage to play many genres from platforms to shooters, from simple sidescrollers to open world role playing games. With the help of steam, my options have been widened even further to the more meaningful games such as Lisa and Beeswing.Now how does this relate to skull girls? To be honest I never really got engaged in the idea of fighting games. My first (and only proper) experience was Mortal Kombat for the PlayStation 3 but it was short lived after realizing that having to do tricky manoeuvres with the controller and winning constantly in story mode by button mashing was less engaging then dying over and over again and being determined to play again in Telleglitch: die more edition, ironically. The reason for this review you won’t see many on the steam store page is that it’s coming from an experienced first timer. I will say right now that it’s the best game to start in if you’re interested in the genre because of a proper, in-depth tutorial that you won’t see in many fighting games. But if you’re interested in the other details the game has, I will tell you the lows and highs of this game.GameplayThe game itself (if you somehow still haven't noticed) is a fighting game but with a fighting style different from Mortal Kombat and the old street fighter games. The fighting itself is based on the idea of juggling, when you hit someone they are put into a stun lock and the opponent can’t do anything about it, but you can do combos with more finesse and skill put into it then the previouse games i mentioned. But that's easier said than done. You have to put hours into a type of character you want if you get the most out of it because, unlike Mortal Kombat, if you attempt to button mash against an experienced player, you will get knocked out in less than 20 seconds and they would probably mock you, just like what happened to me. But the best thing about it is that you can’t be stun locked forever. If you do manage to do a long combo, the opponent can push you back which makes matches fair. fighters are very well diverse with different fighting styles for any player with a personal preference and all have their strength and weaknesses. You also going to need a controler and amazingly PS4 controlers are combatable with skullgirls and make gameplay smother and let you do faster combos. So it’s best to pick this game if you want to have a balanced fight and, don't worry about the DLC characters because the game gives you open beta which has access to all characters, unless you want story mode and speaking of which-PresentationLike most fighting games, each character has their own story mode with different branches in the universe of skull girls. The story itself is surprisingly dark. The world when you see it for the first time is like what you see in a 1940's cartoon but the events in the game is what you would see in a movie like Goodfellas. It all looks good until the end where you can't trust your friends. If the game secretly slips in the violent imaginations from Neoscavenger (its text based if you didn't figure it out) the atmosphere wouldn't change that much. The stories for the characters always end abruptly so don't play if you want closure in your stories. the art style for the game is gorgeous and its best selling point is the animation. the game holds a Guinness world record for number of frames in each fighter. Each fighter with an average of 1439 frames. you can tell the developers really puts in a lot of heart for its presentation on the world.ConclusionTo put this into perspective again, if you’re interested in the confusing and scary world of fighting games, get this game. If you bring friends around for some bonding moments the game might make you laugh with some of the characters moves (particularly peacock) if they haven't seen the story mode yet, or go online to get better and make some new friends like me. If you want a deep narrative or some enjoyable brain dead game play, go play Telleglitch, Ubermosh for some simple, yet engaging game play or Lisa or Beeswing for a meaningful and probably life changing experience."
