,Recommended,245170,16201108,"Posted: 5 June, 2015",all,Hann,"Disclaimer: I'm still a newb.If you're worrying about whether you can play on a keyboard, I play on a keyboard and have no problems relating to using it. BnB combos are perfectly capable of being executed on a keyboard.Feedback is oomphy. Hits are satisfying. Controls are fluid. Oh yeah, there's backdash-canceling, which is pretty damn nice to have. Everything you expect to have from a fighting game is there. Netcode works pretty damn well.If you want to get into fighting games, this is the most welcoming as it will get out of the box. An excellent tutorial introducing core mechanics is present. Finish it. A more in-depth guide on using the training mode frame data and punishing would be better though.This game is solid. Find a friend to play with and figure out the mechanics. Be prepared for significant time investment if you want to ""git gud"", because that's what fighting games are. If you're new to FGs you will struggle at first, but once you get used to the timing and rhythm picking up other moves become considerably easier.Game has pretty lenient hit-confirm windows, no ridiculous combo input requirements/windows/links unless you're going for the insanely high damage combos, in which case you deserve your damage.I like the artstyle, the announcer and the music. They all fit together quite well.Don't expect to launch the game, and be able to go toe-to-toe with people who have put a decent amount of time into learning characters and combos. As is with many other games, you will have to put time into something you want to be good at. Find people who are slightly better than you, or of equal skill level to play with.Also, purple Filia is best Filia."
