,Recommended,245170,8441955,"Posted: 30 December, 2013",all,Demon Games,"With the very few days I had to play it, my review of it will be kept brief: Skullgirls is a game I can go back to time and time again to challenge a friend against with a 1v2 (sometimes 1v3) battle.Characters are nice, controls are fine on keyboard (I have never had an arcade pad, so IDK if that would be better), and story makes sense (eg. Ms. Fortune not liking Cerebella due to the fact that Ms. Fortune hates the Medici mafia, and Vitale Medici is the adoptive father of Cerebella), but is sometimes boring.Overall, the game is very fun to play, but I don't really care as much for the story EXCEPT for Peacock/Patricia (Peacock's name before her body was mutilated and becoming a robot) and the relationship between her and Marie (the current Skullgirl in the game), due to the fact that both of them were orphaned during the war and forced into slavery by a group funded by the Medici Mafia.Also, some characters will have dialog pre-battle between the two of them (Watching from a video, Leviathan (Squigly's parasite), comments that Samsom (Filia's parasite) has gone ""too far"" and when Parasoul is defeated, she mentions to Filia that she is being ""...used.""). Overall, the game is great, but the story could be a TINY bit more fun/polished, then it would be SUPERB.EDIT: It has been months since I made this review, and I now am going back to give my second thoughts on this game: The game is practically the same, but now that I have had the time to play most of the characters, I can appreciate the story even further.I never mentioned the tutorials in my previous review, and I can say this in 3 words: Greatest tutorial ever.I enjoyed playing Skullgirls with my good friend NoblePariah when we would go 1 v however many he chose. Everyone has a style of gameplay that they are most comfortable with, and mine would be fast and furious, so Ms. Fortune happened to be one of my favorite characters.I also had 