,Recommended,245170,7811529,"Posted: 28 November, 2013",all,AmericanSmeagol,"A twitchy love note to the era of Capcom fighters with 99 hit combos. Not an easy game to master, but that shouldn't stop you from trying this mostly-female fighter. A robust tutorial will get novices into fighting shape, and the AI is challenging in its own right. For those who venture online, a wealth of competition awaits, but most are god-like compared to you (unless you have a natural knack for this sort of game). It's because of this high competitive level that I recommend this game for those looking for something to invest time into. If you want depth, a steeper learning curve and a rewarding payoff then this game is for you. Flashy combos are the norm here, and an anti-infinite system keeps the play from becoming a dull loop of the same five moves.Fights have an odd structure for the newcomer, but anyone who has played a versus title should feel at home here. A team can consist of one, two or three characters with health and damage scaling higher in favor of one-lady squads and lower as you add to the pile. There are team-up attacks, tag-out supers and tag knockouts (moves that knock the active fighter out of the ring and force in a partner to take her place). One versus one matches get the typical Street Fighter round structure where best of 3 takes the cake. If even one side chooses more a team of fighters, you only get ""one more once"" to make it happen.What I like most about this game is the constant updates. MikeZ and co add to the endless beta all the time, and they are mostly transparent about the balance work they do. This excites the part of me that loves fighters, and wants that ""inside look"" into how they're made.What I like least about this game is something I can't fault it for, because I knew what I was buying into. I've never been good at the MvC fighters, and just like those yesteryear blockbusters, one false step can kill you in this game. I suggest that you spend time on the AI and in training before venturing online. Competition is stiff and can be frustrating. BUT! The GGPO implementation is awesome! You can actually see the ping and make frame adjustments based on the game's recommendations. It's a very helpful way to lose without lag. =)Learn the basics, go through the tutorial and enjoy this masterpiece of a fighter. Or load up SFIV and shoryuken someone for the umpteenth time. Your choice."
76561197995491515,Recommended,245170,9914130,"Posted: 23 April, 2014",all,2gud,"The term ""babby's first fighting game"" ceases to be adequate. And I don't mean that in a negative sense ethier. Skullgirls is a truely deep, complex, fast-paced fighter, while keeping easily accessible to newcomers. A word of the wise: PRACTICE PRACTICE PRACTICE AND PRACTICE SOME MORE. Online players can and will beat your head open freqently. Thankfully you'll get beaten cuse they have more skill then you, instead of frame delay or lag. The game runs excellently even on older machines and the servers work beautifully with little if any lag."
