,Recommended,245170,11691495,"Posted: 13 August, 2014",all,VGGuy95,"[EDIT 12/3/2015: Fixed some problems with this review to make it more relevant with the current game.](Note that this is solely based on playing offline so far with about 30+ hours put into the game. I also suck at 2D fighting games.)Pros: So far this game is probably one of the best fighting games on Steam. It has by far the best sprites I have ever seen in terms of both art design and frame count, and so far has been consistently at 60 FPS making the game very intense and hectic experience. The game has probably the best tutorial for 2D fighting games I've ever seen, which is surprising since this is an indie game, and the training room is very useful compared to other games. All characters (including the DLC and ""joke"" characters) all feel very unique and different from one another, with usually the DLC characters having a much larger difficulty curve to use.Cons: These are minor nitpicks at best. For one, you can still play on a keyboard like I have with little problems; however certain commands with be much harder to do without Macros. These can include double P, double K, throws. However the one issue with a keyboard that can't be fixed using Macros are 360 direction motions, which are near impossible to do on a keyboard. I also feel like the game should allow you to have more optional Macros for said problems. The game has a rather limited roster (8 characters for the vanilla build and 5 DLC characters with 1 free ""joke"" character. DLC characters are somewhat pricey (though this is justified as they were free for a limited time).Overall, I'd say definitely get this game. Its made by a small indie group that clearly are fighting game fans, and want to create the perfect 2D fighting game. Plus, the game is only $15, so its fairly cheap."
