76561198071429626,Recommended,245170,19559319,"Posted: 7 December, 2015",all,Angel,"Skullgirls is a 2D action fighter consisting of beautifully hand drawn frames of cute and fanservice-y girls (and like 2 guys) with a 1920s setting to their story. This is a fighting game that is similar to MvC2 with the team setups and decently long combo routes (might seem endless to newer players). Each character has their own individual feel and playstyle (even the reskin character surprisingly) with the small roster of 14 characters. Even if you aren't a regular to fighting games, this game is great to pick up with friends (of equal skill levels) and just enjoy a night of classic fighting games with cute girls. Also if you are a weeb, the game has japanese voices, anime skins and references.GraphicsThe game has amazing visuals, all hand drawn and totalling over 1000 frames for each character, the backgrounds are amazing (you can even snag some of these backgrounds for your steam profile pic upon crafting the badge).MusicThe game features music that is styled around the 1920s contemporary era, with jazzy tracks and some cartoony ones. The soundtrack is amazing for what they tried to emulate and really makes this indie go above and beyond.ControlsWhile the game is compatible with Xbox, PS4 and other gamepads including fight-sticks, the game runs surprisingly well on keyboard (which is what I use). Keep in mind you do need a mechanical keyboard, as regular keyboards may drop inputs due to ghosting/rollover, if you don't have any controllers or a keyboard with anti-ghosting/rollover, you might have a hard time. That being said I would recommend a hitbox setup on keyboard (https://puu.sh/wLcYO.png), you can also use wasd if you really want.Single-playerAlthough it is a fighting game, you always gotta have a story mode to go along with it for those of us who would never dream of going online (or just have no friends to play it with). That being said the story mode that is offered is shown in a visual novel style, with scrolling text and sprites followed by fighting cpu opponents that appear. If you have the 2nd encore DLC, the story mode will also feature full voiceacting which is quite exceptional. That being said the story mode is still well worth the money for what you get; each individual character story draws out their background and personalities. Although the story mode feels a little short, each story was still quite satisfying for me. Word of advise, don't do Fukua's story first.GameplayBefore I talk about the game, I just need to say that the tutorial is fantastic, lots of the concepts are shared with other fighting games so you're not doing the tutorial for just skullgirls, you're doing the tutorial for fighting games in general. So don't worry if you can't finish the tutorial in one go, since it gets pretty challenging (looking at you chapter 4, lessons 4-7), just go play some actual games and come back to do it later.This is my first fighting game, so I cant really compare this to other fighting games.However, the gameplay feels nice and smooth, blocking and hit confirming have clear animations for you to react to. Combos feel lenient enough to do even on 200 ping (screw you one frame links, barely any of those here) provided you have learned them first. Games can be played with up to 3 characters and is balanced regardless of how many you and your opponent picks(making 3v1s fair to an extent). Since this game is more combo based than a game like SFV, combos are decently long, 3-5 chains before you can act again, however the game implements a system called IPS which will trigger if your opponent makes a combo too long, allowing you to ""burst"" out of it and push them away if it connects.Instead of longer combos higher level players will do what is called a reset, which is intentionally dropping the combo and hitting you where you least expect it, thus pulling off what seems to be an 'endless' combo. Characters are fairly balanced, with no 1 character being super op, so ignore those tier lists. The games super moves, aka ""blockbusters"" all have a flashy cinematic that is played when executed along with the characters unique super move, these look and feel great to use(when you actually hit them).Multi-playerAlright, we all know that multiplayer is the most important thing in fighting games, so how does skullgirls hold up?For starters, Skullgirls adapts the GGPO netcode, which helps reduce ping/lag. Skullgirls has two main online modes, quick match and lobby play. Lobby play gives you the ability to make a lobby for up to 8 people, who can all play at the same time, each playing 1 opponent (Ie, a 1v1, 1v1, 1v1, 1v1 style), if there is an odd number of people who have readied up, the odd one out will spectate a match. Lobbies are great for playing a variety of people at the same time, provided that they don't glitch out sometimes in which case you'll have to remake the lobby.Onto Quick match, which is the notorious mode that makes many people quit. Quick match used to matchmake based on skill (or hours played, idk) but since the online match mode was not that populated, they changed it just to match based on ping to give people matches to play rather than waiting forever. This is quite discouraging for many new players when they start quick match and face a player with hundreds of hours who will seemingly endless combo them due to the lack of experience. So a word of warning, if you are new, DON'T DO QUICK MATCH (unless you like getting destroyed), you're better off going to lobbies, there will usually be one for casual beginner matches (if there isnt a lobby for beginners, you can totally make one yourself).ConsWhile i may be biased towards the game, I will still list common negatives I come across frequently.Learning curve, like any fighting game, to play the game well, you need to hit up training mode of a couple hours to work on combos and movesets, while the game does make inputs for special moves easier, theres no denying you still need to practise combos alone to even fight against other higher skilled players.Lack of ingame online players, the game usually sits around 200-400 players on any given day, this means that quick match will be filled with high level players who stick around and new players will always get destroyed and most likely quit the game because they feel discouraged after getting perfected. This is the main negative point for this game I feel as a fighting game is heavily based upon its community. While there are lots of nice players within the skullgirls community, sometimes you just can't find someone to play with.If you don't have any friends to play this game with and you are a new player, or just a player who wants to get better, I would highly consider joining the Skullgirls reddit discord and the Skullgirls get gr8 steam group, it sucks that you need to use discord to find players around your skill level, but its the most our community can do at this point. Skullheart forum is good toToo much fanservice, some of you many not like the depiction of over the top fanservice this game uses or just don't like the artstyle, or 'anime' fighters. Of course this could also be a positive for you depending on how you look at it ;)SummaryWorth a buy - I would highly recommend this game if you are a fighting game fan and like the anime-ish artstyle and MvC2 fighting mechanicsWorth a buy only on sale - Would highly reccomend a purchase on sale if you are interested in getting into fighting games. As well as a cool fighting game to play with your buddies on a friday night. Even for just the story mode, may be worth the price on sale.Not worth a buy - Fighting games aren't your thing and your not a weeb. Only interested in quick matches. Don't use discord(where the communities at).Keep in mind I am slightly biased towards the game cause its so"
