,Recommended,245170,7830824,"Posted: 29 November, 2013",all,Sekacnap,"Skullgirls is a nice heavy dose of the familiar topped with a delicious, interesting theme and wonderful personality. The actual mechanics in play are nothing out of the ordinary, you'll be using standard 2D fighter controls to pull off mix-up combos, cancels, special moves and power-bar depleting ""showstoppers."" If you've played any other fast-paced 2D fighter such as Guilty Gear or BlazBlue then you'll be instantly comfortable with the controls and speed of the game. Skullgirls is extremely accessible with a detailed tutorial explaining everything a beginner fighter player would need to know. There's even in-depth character tutorials that explain what each character's special abilities are useful for and how to work them into combos. Within a few hours I was able to start stringing together 25+ hit combos and playing on Hard difficulty and I'm only an intermediate fighting game player.While Skullgirls doesn't do much to innovate at its core, it makes up for this by hitting a home run in the area that matters the most in fighting games, the characters. Each Character is full of personality and is easily distinguishable from the rest in terms of visuals, motif and mechanics. No two characters feel the same. Even the stereotypical doppleganger character (who uses other fighter's skills) feels unique since the borrowed abilities aren't just copy-pasted from their source, they're more like attacks the source character would use but doesn't. I find myself interested in each character, wanting to hear what they have to say, to watch their personalities in action and the story mode, while short and linear, does a great job at showcasing these characters through beautiful still-frame cutscenes.Speaking of the art, Skullgirls is gorgeous!  Its vectored sprites are crisp and the animation is silky smooth. The whole game operates under a jazzy, psuedo-noir/art deco/theater theme that infiltrates every aspect of the game. From the music to the menus to the cutscenes, Skullgirls stays consistent to it's theme and makes the whole experience a coherent one.My only real complaint about Skullgirls is that there are far too few characters at the moment. Since you can play with up to three characters on a team at once, with a roster of about 9 playable characters, playing through arcade mode will have you seeing repeat upon repeat. Thankfully it looks like more characters will be added over time as there is already a DLC character up for purchase.In conclusion, Skullgirls is a ton of fun. It may not do anything out of the ordinary, but what it does, it excels at. I would easily recommend this game as it is an accessible, addicting 2D fighting experience.8/10"
