,Recommended,245170,9294113,"Posted: 28 February, 2014",all,ayeeitslucien,"I had heard of Skullgirls a while ago, didn't purchase it because I had never really bought into the 2D fighting genre.  Then I had some spare change, decided to give it a go simply because the artwork was incredibly impressive.This game is so much deeper than it appears: from a first glance, it's a bunch of scantily clad female characters duking it out through clunky stories with little to no exposition.  But in reality, it is a beautifully animated and well constructed game with intense gameplay (depending on your level of ability), limitless combo possibilities and very challenging gameplay that can be difficult to pick up, but rewarding when you finally get the knack of chaining combos together and holding your own against tougher AI's.A word to the wise, however: if you're thinking about lobby/online play, don't do it until you're incredibly seasoned.  I've only been playing this game a couple weeks, I've tried two online matches, haven't gotten a single hit in.  The players there are incredibly skilled and competitive, and have mastered chaining, cancelling and all the techniques to maximize their damage potential, so practice as much as possible until you've mastered a character or two before you try it out, otherwise it's honestly a waste of your (and their) time.Overall, fantastic game, definitely reccommended."
