76561198114730270,Recommended,245170,11323698,"Posted: 19 July, 2014",all,MrExtravagant,"Skullgirls is perhaps the prime example of what every modern fighting game should try to be when it comes to gameplay, plot, and overall involvement of the creators. The gameplay is smooth and responsive, feeling just like a fighting game should feel. The game will normally run very smoothly on a standard computer with the exception of a certain fight near the end of the game's story and arcade modes. Fortunately, during the fight, the game is still smooth enough to play without effect upon performance.While the basics of the game's plot are simple, the intertwined storylines discovered throughout the game's story mode reveal how deep the story of Skullgirls runs, creating a strange and interesting world which is a blast to delve into. The characters are unique and memorable, each having their own personality, appearance, quirks, etc. which set them apart from the others. This much detail was even put into the unplayable side characters seen in the story, making them just as memorable.The art in the game is unbelievably gorgeous. Every character, stage, and even the menus looks alive. The attention to detail put into everything is admirable. The backgrounds in certain stages will even change, ensuring that you'll never know what you'll see when you go to them.The gameplay is similar to that of the Street Fighter series and it's similar counterparts, and it implements the common concepts such as the ""Hyper Meter"" which allows you to pull of your character's strongest attacks. However, Skullgirls uses a rather interesting concept. Like the Marvel vs Capcom series, you can play tag-matches. However, Skullgirls allows you to pick your roster size and strengthens or weakens characters accordingly, which adds a rather unique feel to the fights.Lab Zero (specifically Skullgirls creators Mike Zaimont and Alex Ahad) is well involved with the community, often listening and researching issues pointed out by players and correcting them in patches. Other than this, they constantly update on upcoming game information and events, and even go as far as to add jokes to the game or even start funding campaigns for additional game conent. Lab Zero truly seems to care about their community and wants to hear their input and be involved with its members.The game has very few problems. First and formost is the small roster of fighters. At this moment in time, there are only thirteen characters in game (fourteen if the non-canon Fukua is counted). However, Lab Zero is currently in development of three more characters, and perhaps we'll see even more in the future, so hopefully, this is merely a temporary problem. Another issue many critics of the game have is of the heavy fanservice. While I won't deny that it's there, it hasn't really affected the game for me, since I usually overlook this sort of thing. And while it it prevelent troughout the game, it usually isn't that distracting, or , if it is, it's put somewhere that will keep it from stealing attention from the rest of the action.All and all, other than it's minor problems, Skullgirls is the perfect fighting game. With balanced gameplay, immersive story, and fun, addictive action, this should be in every fighting enthusiast's library."
