,Recommended,245170,8633055,"Posted: 9 January, 2014",all,vaporFLO,"Skullgirls is not only very tight as a fighting game, but it is also *the* most accessible one I've seen, without sacrificing depth or skill. Indeed, that quality ends up enriching the experience.As a fighting game, nearly every fixing is here, from tag teams, complete with tag-in attacks, assists, and Dynamic Hyper Combos, multi tiered supercombos, aerial combos and launchers, resets, OTG's, and more. Impressively, it manages to cram all this into one game, without making it forced. For example, in order to accomodate various player styles, one may choose to use 1-3 characters, all three options within the realm of balance. Another of it's great triumphs is that it provides a solution to one of the worst problems in such games like MvC: the dreaded infinite. The IPS (Infinite Protection System) was designed to allow players to escape overly repetitive combos at a push of a button. This ensures that giant combo strings are still possible, but players now have to be more creative with how they pummel an enemy.It's accessibility is also a great boon, in that even those who have never tried Street Fighter before have a good chance to improve themselves quickly, but properly, in no small part due to its excellent tutorial. The tutorial not only gives the usual basics lessons for those who have never thrown a Hadouken before, but it also shows the more esoteric aspects of 2D fighting games, such as mix-ups, movements, and such. Not only does this help newbies get into the game, but even the veterans can learn or practice the advanced skills. There's even basics for each character for those who don't want to have to scan through movesets. This is not the only aid, as even the controls maintain the same feel, in that one doesn't have to snap arcade sticks trying to do instant 720 degree spins. The various attacks have easier inputs, most of which are just like MvC's special attack movement + double attack button, and yet almost all avoid overlapping each other. The hardest input is a 360 spin, which the game itself actually has a system to add leniency, so that one doesn't end up jumping instead of grappling at a critical moment.The game's onlt real weak point at the moment is the rather small roster, however each of them maintain their own niche to add uniqueness, as well as more characters to come in the future. They vary from the classic all-rounder, the heavy grappler, and the more unusual ones, such as the catwoman with a detachable and controllable head. The art style and final boss might be more debatable, however, if several generations have added tons of half-naked muscular males, I don't see why we should be so shy of some somewhat normal but revealing designs for the ladies. Oh yes, in case you didn't see from the various screenshots and videos, amusingly, the usual gender ratio is reversed, with the majority of the cast being female. As for the final boss, some people are masochistic enough to want to fight an SNK Boss, but that's down to preference.I'm not an expert on sound design, but I never found the music to be annoying to the ears, in fact, the music is subtle enough to be ignored during most fights. Still, it isn't torture, so that's nice.In the end, this is 2D fighting refined. It still has the depth that the people come for, but really tries to evolve the genre by trying to remove the fat, with the result being not only a well-executed game, but a rather unique one. 8.5/10"
