,Recommended,245170,9576325,"Posted: 20 March, 2014",all,ʇsǝq sʍouʞ ɹǝʌǝu,"I am a bit conflicted about whether or not I can recommend this game wholeheartedly.First of all, I'm an amateur at fighting games. I used to play some street fighter and a few other fighting games that came out on a couple consoles, but I was never anywhere near ""good"" by any competitive standard. So keep that in mind.So, where to start...The art style and world construction are both excellent. The game takes place in a fantasy world of the 1920s or '30s, populated by animal people as well as humans, and of course the martially minded female characters who possess varying levels of magic or otherwise supernatural abilities. As you can see, the art is heavily inspired by Art Deco, and while the world itself is rather fanciful, both the setting and the art feature heavy dark tones. The soundtrack is spot on, in my opinion, featuring nice 1920s style lounge jazz with silky smooth female vocals. Then, of course, there's the fan service, but I don't think I need to say much about that; I'm sure you already know what you think of that all by yourself.Unfortunately, the writing for the story sections is pretty flimsy. I don't know anybody who gets into a fighting game for the story, but if you're going to do it I think you should probably do it right. Especially when it's just a few terse lines struggling to tie together two fights, a little bit of good writing goes a long way.And, what about the gameplay itself?I think that the story and arcade modes are beginner friendly, and both modes are fun when you've got a little time to kill. Not only do the various difficulty levels help you find your own, but the challenges were such that I felt I was learning more about how to use my character of choice effectively. With the move encyclopedia (accessible in battle), and the practice mode, I think there was a good effort made at making the game accessible and learnable by those newer or not as dedicated to fighting games, like myself.Also, there a number of cool features, such as the ability to choose one character, or a 2 or 3 man tag-team for your versus battles (with each character having 1/2 or 1/3 of max health, depending on the choice), and in 2-round battles the winner keeps their health from the first round, gaining an additional bar when that's depleted.The multiplayer is really the meat of any fighting game, though; this is where it all hinges. And I do think that the multiplayer can be really fun against someone of a similar skill level, at least when you're both low to mid-level (more on this later). However, the multiplayer infrastructure is set up in such a way that finding someone of a similar skill level is the exception rather than the rule. It selects based, it seems, only upon ping (and not terribly well, even just by that standard. Expect a lot of 260ms ping fights). The result are a lot of really one sided fights that aren't any more fun for the winner than the loser (even as infrequently as I get to be the winner, haha).Additionally, playing the online multiplayer has raised some doubts about whether Skullgirls is likely to be much fun among the top level players (although I can't really say, not being one). There has been some talk of anti-juggle protection, but regardless of what that actually means a player who knows what they're doing can throw you around until the cows come home; that is to say juggle you, in the ways that leave you completely vulnerable. Once they get you into one of these the result is invariably 60-90% of your max health gone before your character is able to stand up, and then the rest is just mop-up duty. Doesn't this mean that play between two high level players is entirely focussed on who gets in the first hit?  Maybe I'm just too bad to see or know the way out of these juggle chains. It's hard for me to say.The online multiplayer also lacks any sort of communication, which is definitely best for a fighting game (communication would almost certainly just mean insults and yelling), but it also means that there's no way to develop any community or ties within the game, and means that there's noone giving any advice to those who aren't so good.Finally, this game is being patched and updated fairly regularly, but it's not an early access, so you can't expect much of this to change in the future.Conclusion; I DO recommend this game for more amateur players, but only if you're going to play it with friends (or only solo, but where's the fun in that?). Serious players, choose for yourself. The problems that I've listed may be in every fighting game, but that doesn't make them any more likely to attract new blood to the genre. Is this why only the most pigheaded of the competitive seem to play them seriously?"
