,Recommended,245170,7918745,"Posted: 4 December, 2013",all,Jab Rose,"I'm not fighting game expert. Plop me into a fighting game tournament for any fighter that doesn't have a block button (So pretty much any game except mortal kombat 9) And I'll be knocked out in 10 seconds. However, I still love playing them because they're adrenaline packed and exciting expiriences. I'll admit I'm casual, and I have no interest in the competitive circuit, but let me tell you this. I. ♥♥♥♥ing. Love. Skullgirls. Take away the fighting mechanics and all that, this game just OOZES charm with each character and stage. The story mode isn't as complex as MK9 Or Injustice, but it's still pretty interesting, with a great background for each character. You can really see their personalities when they fight, and it's just so amazing. The game does have a great tutorial for New commers, however I always found the game to be a bit too geared towards the arcade stick, it doesn't accomadate the button icons for when you're using a keyboard or a gamepad (which I use) So you'll have to do a bit of memorization to learn just what button means what. But once you get the hang of that, this game is just amazing. If you're a newbie like me, I would avoid random online matches since, trust me, you will be DESTROYED by the pro players. Beginner Level lobbies are more friendly. But even then Single player story and arcade on their own can be enough to hold it for a good long while, even though I think they could have added some more to it (Tag team online mode, survivor mode, king of the hill online, etc) Final verdict? Get this game. And then get it for your friends so you can play together. It is worth the 15$ price tag."
