,Recommended,245170,11162761,"Posted: 10 July, 2014",all,Morty Smith,"After spending a good amount of time withing the Tutorial and playing the game in general, I can honestly say that Skullgirls is by far the BEST fighting game I have ever played. I have played Ultra Street Fighter 4, Ultimate Marvel 3 and so on, but, Skullgirls fills some holes those two left me with.The mechanics are so far similar to Marvel which is great. The game flows very closley to that of Ultimate Marvel vs Capcom 3 as well, which works well! The only difference is there is no combo tagging in/out. Which means a Character soley relys on assists ONLY from their partner if he so chooses to have one. This, in term, make this title feel more like King of Fighters 13, which is also amazing.The tutorial mode helps newcomers to the fighting game scene explore what the game is capable of, showing them how to play certain characters tuned to said characters styles of play. This actually helped ME out during my playthrough as I often have trouble determining what characters are what and what situations are best for them.The storyline is different for each character and the online is nearly perfect. The only downside is that you can't play versus a CPU without being in Arcade mode. Its a bit annoying but not a huge deal.I would also like to add this game doesn't take much to run! Which, on a machine like mine, is a huge plus!UPDATE:After sitting with this game as of recently I have some more stellar complaints.This title is still good at it's core. However, the dwindling base of players made it pretty much a shoe-in for keeping in your backlog, never to be played again. The indie dev's who made this title put a lot of care into the game, which sucks because the game itself is still great!I would reccomend a more popular title if you are looking for some solid Multiplayer action, something like Street Fighter 5 or Tekken 7 if you are in the market for a fighting game.Updated Score - 5/10"
,Recommended,245170,10389054,"Posted: 7 June, 2014",all,KSH,"Fighting games for the cheap, perfect for total noobs to fighting games who want a tutorial, works on every toaster known to man from 2009 to today+Good tutorial that can be applied to other fighting games (for the most part)+Easy to understand mechanics+Good lookin' game with nice butts. Thanks, Alex+It's like Marvel 2 combined with Guilty Gear+Variety of character playstyles. There's even a puppet character (Like Zato/Eddie from the GG series)-Might be noob friendly in teaching, but not so much playing online with randoms-You might may or may not hate this game after playing different fighting games and coming back to Skullgirls after a long period of timeWhile I recommend it for beginners, beware that this is a fighting game. Not everyone is a beginner like you. Skullgirl's player base is small, meaning you'll face mainly really good players from as far back as when this game first came out. To get good, you have to lose first: the rule of thumb in any ""game you want to win in""UPDATE: This game has the 2nd Encore update as DLC. Get it if it's past the year 2016 and you want all the DLC characters and target combos to practice withOverall good fighter that welcomes many to the genre. This is actually where I started myself and I will always recommend this game as a start because it teaches you things that is universal to a lot of fighting games."
