76561198031969844,Recommended,245170,23473482,"Posted: 9 June, 2016",all,Martelheur,"As a incredibly quick review, I'd say the following :-stupendous graphics and animation-excellent soundtrack-REFERENCES EVERYWHERE-very cool and well executed dark deco/roaring twenties setting-the roaster may be small, but frankly, with all there is to master in each character - which are all very unique- at least for a beginner, you're not soon to be bored-a lot of stages (i mean come on there's more stages than characters...)-really complete game modes, options, menu, etc...-extremely fun to play whatever your level, especially with a friend besides youThe main downside would be the story mode. I know I'm not supposed to be expecting much from a fighting game, since that's not his point...but still. Even if the artworks are great, the story of each character is shockingly short (doesn't exceed 10 minutes if you don't count the fights). Also, it is poorly told (some of the writing is plain as water, and I'm not speaking about the super predictable situations, events and outcomes, or on the contrary the unexplained lore that's needed to understand the plot), and sometimes even not told at all! I remember times when a fight would occur without ANY explanation at all as for his reason to take place. Just as if there was a fight there to, well, fight...because ♥♥♥♥ that's a fighting game. I mean it's really like "" Hey Samson you wanna eat an ice cream?"" and BOOM *insert fight with random character you didn't even know existed*Last but not least, the dub is somewhat uneven. It's sometimes perfectly fluent, and other times it seems like the voice actor is reciting a lesson.But then again, flawed as it is, the story mode is far from essential to a fighting game, and aside it, everything's almost perfect.That's why I highly recommend it."
