,Recommended,245170,7872248,"Posted: 1 December, 2013",all,Spud,"Skullgirls is an exceptional puzzle game, despite my admittedly short time in it. I'm a lot better at Tetris. This is where I write a review about crap I don't care about so that little silver icon that says I need to write a review stops saying I need to write a review. Does Valve even double check this stuff? I bet they don't.First off, the game is gorgeous and if you disagree I'll hit you in every genital you own. Hand-drawn animations and backgrounds make up the entirety of the visuals, and effects are top-notch as well. There is also a (somewhat small for the time being) cast made almost entirely of girls, girls for every taste. There's your big-breasted sexy evil nurse, and your big-hipped sexy amnesiac schoolgirl, and your big-butt rotten zombie girl with the big worm in her head who was also an opera singer. She reminds me of my ex. Because of the singing, I mean. She had a nice voice. Not because of the worrmmss in her heeaaddddThese visuals seem somewhat wasted on such a game, though. Skullgirls attempts to sell itself through and through as a 'fighting game,' whatever that is, with comparisons to some other crap no one cares about called Marmen vs. Canada or something. I don't know. I bought this because the developers seemed like cool folks who could use my measly ten dollar pre-order to make better games, by which I mean ones that include falling blocks and aren't in the wrong category in the Steam store. Despite the insistence on such things like life bars, 'super' meters that use a different name so they aren't supers, et cetera ad infinitum, at its heart Skullgirls is a very in-depth puzzle game. It revolves around stringing together the longest 'combo' of sequential button presses you can without triggering the function that says your string of button presses is too long and now your opponent can use their string of button presses. Sometimes the developers change this function to work differently. Then the players rework their strings of button presses to circumvent the function again. Where is the L block? There is no L block. There are blocks and Ls but no L blocks.I give this game 9/10 rolling cat heads, it's okay but is obviously sexist, racist, bigot-ist and Marxist along with innumerable other words ending in -ist but somehow not including 'fist.' That's my favorite word ending in -ist. Or -isting. Anyway leave a comment on my Steam zone if you want a pizza roll."
