,Recommended,245170,29271181,Posted: 15 January,all,bizzychoco,"I really love this game. To the point where I have three copies of the game (PC, Vita, PS4). It's not even my main fighting game, but I would call it my favourite. It doesn't have the biggest community, yet I can find people at my skill and have lots of fun. It's a fighting game made by an independent studio, yet it they handle the game well and have good relations with their players, while big name developers (Capcom especially) neglect their players and not fixing their mistakes despite how glaring they are. This is because Skullgirls is a game made for the community, by members of the community.While I could go on about its great art, music, lore and havingTHE BEST TUTORIAL IN FIGHTING GAME HISTORY, the gameplay is what should be highlighted. It feels extremely fast and fluid, rewarding long combos and team synergy similar to MvC2. Landing that sweet, long combo you've been practising in training is a great feeling, one that should be sought after when playing this game. The community, while small, still has a good range of skill levels. And while you may think that online is godlike since players can KO you after two long combos, they actually aren't as good as you think and are closer to your level.To finish up, Skullgirls is one of the best fighting games of the generation but never got its chance to really take off. If you are someone who wants to get into fighting games for a relatively cheap price, you should get this game. The tutorial really holds your hand tight and the SG community is full of very helpful people, willing to grow the scene. Skullgirls really had a lot of hard work put into it and it really shows off. This is a must, even for casuals."
