,Recommended,245170,10415589,"Posted: 10 June, 2014",all,oh no oh no no no,"Every character is unique and has a unique moveset (even the joke clone character). The fighting is tight yet flows nicely and the game moves at what I think is the perfect speed for a fighting game. Combos can string from a multitude of attacks and if you're good enough you can win a match with just one long combo. The characters also come in ranges from keepaway zoner to rushdown to grappler and they play these roles to the extreme. This approach of ""every character is OP so nobody is OP"" makes the characters fun to play as and see what matches can come about. There are little times you can say ""if only x can do x role move"" because they usualy can. The ability to also choose from 1-3 characters in a match each with custom assists adds to the freshness every round can bring.The love and dedication that was put into Skullgirls is one of the most apparent factors when playing. Hand drawn backgrounds and hand drawn frames for each character show how much work was put into Skullgirls. Each character from concept to finalizaiton is made to be completely unique in terms of fighting style and personality so no two characters play the same. Valentine excels in movement to quickly lockdown an opponent with a series of rapid attacks while Ms. Fortune utilizes her dismembered head to trap the opponent in two sided combos where they never know where next attack will come from. All this layered over a great soundtrack A small thing to mention are the multiples quotes given for same attacks which make characters .This is getting too long so I'll just wrap it up and say yes you should get Skullgirls. No, I wil not get it for you. Unless it's on sale. But that depends.By the way there is no joke clone character. Don't look for her."
