,Recommended,245170,10001039,"Posted: 2 May, 2014",all,Zastavan,"This is a really pleasant fighting game. From the art style to the moves and controls. But unfortunately its missing depth and features that you only begin to notice the deeper you go. Its like playing an FPS where you can't jump or crouch, it takes some time to realize how big of an issue this really is and how much it sucks.The art style is very pleasant with my favorite character being Peacock becuase she is sooooo cute ^_^Its easy to pickup even to people who don't play much fighters and even with 6 hours in I can still lose to a guy with none in it. Now Im not very good at fighters and have never much been into them but I really like Skullgirls. Its fast paced with alot of action but getting knocked up and stuck in a combo chain is a real issue for high skill tiers and by skill I simply mean memorizing a specific order of hitting buttons to win. Which players actually do and it ruins the game. So if you want a fighting game for people that play alot of fighting games Skullgirls is not it and you should just go to KOF or SF or something like that instead of this. That said for people who don't play fighting games is what skullgirls is probably best for as it dousn't have the deepness of other games which is good for noobs but terrible for higher skill tiers as issues develop and the game becomes garbage when even the best players cant do anything when stuck in a long chain that kills them.The singleplayer is pretty underwheling with the AI not being terribly good at the game and the end boss being rather cheap atleast in what I played.  Lets say you play a boxing game and the final boss is a brick wall that throws things at you, its a♥♥♥♥♥♥bossfight I have no impetus to want to play.Multiplayer is where its at and its great especially with friends. But the problems start when you play with people that take the game competatively instead of casually. Skullgirls is a decent game but not a terribly good fighting game. I would say bordering on a bad fighting game. One of the main issues is getting stuck in knock ups or long chains of moves that can take all your health or a good bit of it while your basically defenceless. There is no combo breaking or anything that would allow a player to break out of this sort of knock up chain. Unfortunately many online players basically rely completely on this tactic to win. Which isn't good gameplay and will only make the online gameplay die more quickly.So play with friends. Don't play with randoms. On a technical note lag is often noticable and its hard to find people to play with that are close. Whatever people say about the ""great"" netcode it really isn't that great that it defies basic physics. It only works around reality. So it dousn't make a ♥♥♥♥♥♥ connection non♥♥♥♥♥♥it only makes it seem less terrible than it is.Theres only a few characters to play but they are all well made and special from one another. The moves range in difficulty but are all pretty easy once you learn them. There isn't a terribly large number of moves either so its a pretty decent fighting game for people not really into fighting games.Its a fighting game, theres really not that much to say about it. The arts good. But after so long of playing it off and on I have come to the conclusion this game probably isn't worth more than $10 and maybe $15 if you really really like the art. There just isn't much in the way of mechanics or design, and in all its really lacking in some aspects and it really shows the more you play.In a previous review I was way to positive about the game, its best if you can play with friends who are at similiar skill levels but this game will never be on the competative level of the big boys because its to simple. Simplicity is good for casual or noob players but for people knee deep in fighting games its just to simple and lacking. The art is really good though and its very fun, but the issues really do get in the way.TL:DR Its babies first fighting game, but not something for more experienced players unless you really like the aesthetics."
