,Not Recommended,245170,30506513,Posted: 14 March,all,Kurs'd Arriator,"Skullgirls advertises itself with ""all-new game systems which test the skills of veteran fighting game fans while also making the genre enjoyable and accessible to newcomers.""The former, I don't doubt.The latter is a blatant lie.I am about as much a newcomer to fighting games as there can be, having never touched one before this game. In fact, this sparked my curiosity. A fighting game that's easy to learn? Perhaps thereishope for me. Boy, was I wrong.The first struggle I had to make is button distinguishing in the main menu. What kind of button is ""LK""? After finding out that ""A"" (turning out to be ""LP"") did the trick and accidentally quitting the game AND skipping the intro cinematic, I found out it's bound to Z. Being a German, I rebound it to Y. Okay.Then I found the big flashy ""TRAINING"" option. Well, this looks good. Tutorial? Really! Let's do this!And with every tutorial step the game really set in. Button prompts in the shapes of arrows were soon replaced with somewhat difficult to understand analog stick icons, having patterns drawn onto them like Zs, or Js, to indicate the order of directions required to input. And this was the tutorial for executing special attacks -- which of course made heavy use of these.And finally, my breaking point; Chapter 2-1: Defending against Mix-Ups. After a general definition of Mix-Ups being quick attack combos meant to distract and confuse the enemy into a wrong block so any subsequent hits connect and deal damage, I have received the objective of completely blocking three different mix-up patterns of increasing difficulty. And with hit flash after hit flash my patience chipped away even despite the infinite health, and after being met with the fourth repetition of what was supposed to be a blocking tutorial giving me mere FRAMES to input the correct block button, I actually burst into tears, doubting my skill. Think about it this way: The part that was supposed to teach me how to play made me cry and question my ability to push buttons on a keyboard.So I tried an actual training match against a stationary, non-blocking, non-attacking enemy... and felt though that accomplished just as little, teaching me nothing about how the game worked, or how to enjoy it, or how to play. 5 minutes I just randomly hit the attack buttons, hoping to god something good would come out of it, before calling it a day and writing this review.This game is about as newcomer-friendly as ARMA 3 is in the genre of first-person shooters."
