,Not Recommended,245170,7642725,"Posted: 12 November, 2013",all,nsc,"Skullgirls is on sale, but should you buy it?Now, if you play fighting games, you probably already know if you like skullgirls or not. If you don't play fighting games, should you get into this wonderful genre and should Skullgirls be your entry? Let's take a look.First off, a lot of people I know always say the same thing when I talk to them about fighting games, ""I'm not very good at them."" Putting it lightly, they're wrong, and you probably are wrong too. It's not that you're bad at fighting games, it's that you don't know how to play them.Are you bad at playing an instrument you've never learned? No, you just haven't learned how to play it.So at this point you probably know that you don't want to buy fighting games and play fighting games. After all you don't want to spend time learning how to play, learning what to do. Often people buy special controllers to play fighting games (arcade sticks) which can cost around $100 and right now you are feeling overwhellmed.So why would you want to get into a niche part of a hobby where people tell you to spend $100 on a controller and you need to spend a lot of time learning how to play and what to do.The gameplay of fighting games is without a doubt the most rewarding competitive video game multiplayer experience. If you like the aspect of directly proving that you are better than someone else by beating the crap out of their virtual avatar then fighting games are for you.In many games such as MOBAs or FPS games people will often whine about their bad team caused them to lose, in fighting games there is no team, if they lose it's because they're crap.Now, winning in fighting games appears very simple. Just don't get hit. However it isn't that simple in reality.Skullgirls is centered around broken and unfair mechanics layed out by Capcom's VS series, where long combos are king and if you can't execute these combos you will not win. It doesn't matter if you can hit him 10 times while they hit you once if their one time takes all your life and your 10 hits barely scratch them.On top of that Skullgirls has a long and rocky history involving dramatic changes to how each player combos and how many subsystems interract.At the current installment I find skullgirls has rediculous requirements for combo execution, learning how to preform you combos and the gameplay isn't better than direct competitors to demand these things.Previously my review featured an in depth breakdown of the game, the systems, and did reccomend it  however in my opinion the constant development and changes has really hurt the game and forced people to relearn their combos, relearn their teams, relearn what their assist calls do.For even FGC fans I would call that unforgivable and for new players even more so. Learning fighting games doesn't have to be as hard as skull girls makes it, so do yourself a favor and pass this game up."
