,Recommended,245170,16489407,"Posted: 17 June, 2015",all,Hexie Lambent - ♤,"I bought this game very soon after it was made available, and not even for the panties and boobies.  ""What are you, gay?""  the average internet-goer may inquire, and sir / madame / wolf / otherkin, that is not a question even I can answer, as I identify as a genderfluid planet.For the fightin' game vets, Skullgirls is a 6-button fighter that feels like the perfect middle ground between the tactics of Street Fighter and the combo chaos of Marvel VS Capcom.  The mechanics are varied and unique between the small-yet-growing cast of characters (the only ""Ken"" literally started out as an april fool's joke, and even then it's hardly the same character).  Variable team sizes of 1 to 3 is a huge part of your pre-game choice and playstyle as it directly and dramatically affects the power and health of your individuals and how many assists you get.  The combos chain fluidly, the action stays fast, and wins feel earned.For the newcomers, this is a fantastic introduction to fighting games, or a great one to play casually.  There are step-by-step tutorials, ranging from the basic buttons and mechanics to how each character's unique moves work together.  I had no experience with the infamous insane difficulty leaps between difficulty settings, and there's neat storylines for each character explaining why they're all clawing each other's eyes out in the first place.  The frantic pace makes even button mashing exciting, and all of the aesthetics look friggin' sweet.  Which brings me to my next point...The atmosphere is inviting and flashy, the music is snazzy and classy, and the animations are as smooth and beautiful as the characters.  This is quite literally art in motion, and it all comes together nearly flawlessly.  I don't think I have anything bad to say about this game other than some of the paid DLC (which are offered for free in the first while they are released) but eh, that shouldn't detract from the rest of it.  A steal of an experience for the 3 dollars or so it's on sale for at the time of writing.Oh, and there's a Zone-Tan skin for one of the girls, Squigly.  There is also a Zone-Tan background sprite in the game.  Steam wouldn't allow me to tell me who that is if you don't know.  Among that, there's plenty of other sneaky references and nods to things in places like background characters, voice lines, the moves themselves, and the fighter's color palettes."
