,Recommended,245170,17806595,"Posted: 30 August, 2015",all,Shlongadactyl,gg
76561197999877866,Not Recommended,245170,17118998,"Posted: 18 July, 2015",all,MEITTI,"Now that Robo-Fortune is up and game is starting to get finished for real, might as well throw a review. Cautious not-recommend. The online of this game is pretty much dead in Europe, so you need friends of your own to have fun with this game. As for gameplay, it has its problems. All characters have unique movesets and really creative animation to it (which was what got me interested in the game in the first place since I'm animator myself) but the core meta of the game itself is rather lacking.The main problem is the length of combos. 10 second combos are a norm in the game, even when you know what to do and can break away from one without getting baited into yet another one. 50% of the time you spend in this game is waiting for another persons combo to end, then you doing your own combos. The back & forth is almost nonexistant even in higher level play. The player engagement isnt there because the game takes away the controller from your hand for lengthy periods of time. It is truly a sad state of affairs when other highly competitive genres like MOBAs have faster games than Skullgirls, or at least games that FEEL faster because you cant go and get a beer from your fridge while youre playing them. It shouldnt be this way. I shouldnt be able to feel the game is more fastpaced with games like SMITE, or RTSses. Those games shouldnt have more player involvement than a traditional fighting game.Combos become double the problem when lot of the cool character mechanics get completely ignored in the meta. Why bother doing mindgames and zoning with Sguigly and her cool stances when you can just do the same 15-20 second combos like everyone else? Why bother using the crowd-raising mechanics of Beowulf and do some fun custom wrestling throws when you can just do combos that are way less risky to do and yield more results?Compare to other fighters like Killer Instinct which is all about combos, combo length there is 5-6 seconds at most. Or Guilty Gear where devastating combos are also a reality but only take 3-5 seconds of real-time at most. The problem isnt the fact theres combos in the game, but the fact they take way too long. Getting wrecked by a combo is fine, but it shouldnt take so long as for the receiving player having enough time to start thinking about things other than the game itself. Either making the combos do way more damage, just making matches shorter, or otherwise promoting more back & forth/risk-reward gameplay would fix the issue.Alas the community of the game does not want it to be fixed, and want this game to remain a long-combo galore where versus matches turn into turn-based single-player modes where the referee takes the controller away from one player at a time for lengthy periods. That is why you wont find any newer players or intermediates online, you have to rely on your friends also liking the game and playing with you. I used to have one, until he got fed up by the combo lengths as well. Theres random spikes whenever a new character is up or free weekends are a thing but otherwise the pool of players remains the 100-200 or so players for the reasons stated above. The game didnt even get a place in EVO this year which is extremely sad.Skullgirls is a game you really wish would be better. The animation and visual aspect is great, theres some real good ideas thrown in there especially in the ways some of the characters play, but the core gameplay itself is deeply flawed, goes against the ""easy to learn-hard to master""-rule that makes so many other fighters good, and ultimately is a barren desert where you will face only those same 100-200 or so die-hard proplayers who still keep playing this. If you like doing lengthy combos, this game is for you. If you want an exciting, fast-paced fighter you can easily train your friends to play with? Avoid this one.Heres hoping theres going to be Skullgirls 2, and its going to be more like Guilty Gear or Vampire Savior in gameplay, and less like a long combo bore-fest ""fighter"" where you can read a book on your lap while playing."
