76561198028769894,Recommended,245170,16342966,"Posted: 12 June, 2015",all,Shuvack,"Smoothest animations in 2D fighting games history.That alone kept me glued to the screen, to the point of not actually caring about gameplay and just enjoying beautifylly animated, and jolly ridiculous moves. I made a review based on what I've managed to play during a free weekend; and what I saw was exactly what I would get later on- a well made fighting game with care for the deepest and maybe even useless details; a crowdfunded labour of love, trying to convince its player to love it back.It's worth mentioning that the entry point to it is pretty easy thanks to the big and extremely advanced tutorial, as well as customizeable training mode.I unfortunately suffer from not having a soft button controller, wich would make execution of more advanced moves much easier and comfortable to pull off. Knowing this I'd recommend everyone to have a pad or anything with a stick to do 360s with, several characters need them for some moves; thus you need it if you want to play online.The game might be easy to pick up, but it's still demanding when it comes to expertise. And thanks to me being a ""Tekken kid"", the whole idea of 6 attack button distracts me to no end; but maybe that's just me :( .Contents are satisfying, with 9 base characters, each with a story mode, and each with 25 color pallettes; a handful of stages and a glorious jazzy soundtrack; all for the initial price of 15$.But if you want to get into it, everyone would advise you to pick up the character DLCs (all of wich can be played in the tutorial for free, but nowhere else), and with DLCs comes a little bit more cost- 5 characters, 5$ dollars each, all of which amounts to 25$.So a full game becomes 40$, it all depends on how many hours you are willing to sink into it- it would feel like supporting the devs, or wasting your funds.If you like what you see- I recemmend it without hesitations; if you're unsure- try no DLCs or during sales. Cause it's a gorgeous fighting game that would be a waste to not try out."
