,Recommended,245170,20418287,"Posted: 9 January, 2016",all,TotalTortilla,"As someone who simply adores the genre while simultaneously sucking at almost every game in said genre, Skullgirls is easily my favorite fighting game to date. The mechanics feel great, the art and music are to die for, every character is fun to play as, and pulling off tricky, high-damage combos feels incredibly satisfying. Bonus points awarded for having a tutorial that teaches you more about how to play fighting games, rather than just Skullgirls itself. If you like fighting games or have any interest in getting into them, Skullgirls is definitely a solid choice.That being said, fighting games are a hard genre to get into. You have to accept that you're going to lose pretty much every single match you play online for a while. It will sting pretty hard when you find yourself beaten over and over, but you need to take those losses as lessons. ""What part of my character could I make better use of?"" ""Do I need to work on my footsie game?"" ""What would my opponent do if I tried this on them?"" Fighting games are like intricate games of chess; half of the game is execution, while the other half is mind games - knowing what your opponent is going to do next. Try looking up some tutorials, or even tournament footage to get ideas on what you can improve upon. If you're willing to put in the work to git gud, then you're going to find fighting games are one of the most exciting video game genres around."
