,Recommended,245170,16224643,"Posted: 6 June, 2015",all,SaladSnack,"Skullgirls is a 2D fighting game that is solid for beginners and veterans of fighting games alike. It's a great starting point if you want to learn how to play 2D fighters. The tutorials in Skullgirls are probably one of the best of any fighting game; it teaches you the fundamentals in a simple manner. Gameplay is pretty standard like most fighting games; you have arcade mode, story mode, local and online versus mode. Online is pretty smooth; even against people with 200+ ping, GGPO makes it tolerable. One feature to note is a combo breaker; if a combo extends too long, you can burst out of it. Graphics aren't exactly top notch, but the visuals are great. Backgrounds are detailed and the characters are well drawn. The soundtrack matches the theme, and one of the composers, Michiru Yamane, is notable for having worked on Castlevania games before.Overall, not a bad game, and it's fairly cheap at US$15(non-sale price). If you happen to get it during a sale, get the DLC characters to expand your playable roster. Keyboard is not recommended, I suggest using a gamepad or arcade stick.NOTE: You can fight against people who have the DLC characters; you're just locked out from playing them yourself.Summary:+ Tutorials are great, teaches you how to play+ Visually pleasing, but nothing spectacular+ Soundtrack is appropriate and enjoyable+ Most cases, no major issues with online multiplayer= Gameplay is pretty standard for a fighting game; not a bad thing= When not on sale; the game with all the DLC characters costs around US$30= As with most fighting games, keyboard is unsuitable; play using a gamepad or fight stick"
