,Recommended,245170,12285995,"Posted: 28 September, 2014",all,Visiorex,"PLEASE READ IN ITS ENTIRETY, THIS REVIEW IS LENGTHY BUT CONCISE:This is a really nice fighting game. Despite my meager sum of hours at this point (7.4) and my limited experience with fighting games in general, this game really helped me learn the general meta of fighting games through its insanely well put together tutorial. Any beginner should really pick this as their first fighting game if they can, and if they've been having trouble getting into fighting games, this game should put them right in there. The only catch is that if you want to get into it, you HAVE to play the tutorial. That said, my assumption is that this game has enough depth for any experienced player to hop right in and enjoy (of course utilizing the tutorial and training mode to get comfortable with each character).In terms of the playability, I am pleased. It has liquid smooth gameplay (as far as I'm concerned) and runs at a rock solid 60 on my Lenovo ThinkPad Yoga. I personally play with the keyboard, since my options involve a 360 controller and said keyboard (and trust me, the controller doesn't do this game any favors - the keyboard is DEFINITELY the better choice). That being said, if you don't have a fight stick, don't feel like you can't play this game and if you have a controller, don't use it. One character I've run into that gives me issue with not having a fight stick is Cerebella, because one of her blockbusters involves a 360 motion, and that is difficult to replicate with wasd. Another character that gave me trouble was Peacock, because one of her blockbusters involved cancelling a grab into said blockbuster, and I was having trouble because my keyboard is bluetooth, and the latency is too slow (so basically this one is negligible, since I did manage to pull off the blockbuster in the end).RECOMMENDED KEYBOARD BINDINGS:W-UPS-DOWNA-LEFTD-RIGHTJ-LKK-MKL-HKU-LPI-MPO-HPSPACE-PauseENTER-SelectIf desired (for team play):;-Macro 1P-Macro 2Leave all other commands unbound.The character cast is pretty small, two of which (Squigly and Big Band) I do not have, so that leaves me with 8 playable characters: Double, Filia, Ms. Fortune, Peacock, Cerebella, Valentine, Parasoul and Painwheel. However, each character comes with an amount of depth that shows each of them has been crafted with utmost care. Unfortunately, the amount of play time I have does not allow me to discuss the balancing of each of the characters, so I'll leave that to someone with more time in the game.This game is for one to two players. The gameplay is pretty good, and this I CAN talk about in terms of balance, because there are three ways to play, and each player doesn't necessarily need to choose the same one. The three ways are: one character, two characters and three characters. To balance it out, the damage and health of each character is divided by the amount of characters on a team. When a player has more than one character, the player can use assists, even during blockbusters, and you can also switch between characters, which CAN deal damage.I have not used the ranked internet play, though I hear the netcode is solid. I HAVE done two person local play, and this works very well, as I was using my keyboard and the other person was using my controller.Some extra good points involve the simplest key binding process I have ever seen in a fighting game and also a phenomenal jazzy soundtrack that I bought and consequently listen to in order to relax or do work.In terms of the poor points in this game - I personally can only think of one, and that's the fact that I'm not proficient enough with fighting games to find any flaws.Hope this review was helpful,Visiorex"
