76561198064491697,Recommended,245170,15423758,"Posted: 17 April, 2015",all,Shinbowl AKA KissShotHeart,"This is my first review so please bare with me on thisPros,*unique, dynamic artstyle*great tutorial mode*even with a cast of about 8 characters(doing this off the top of my head) its still pretty diverse,*no 2 characters are even remotely the same*Infinite Prevention System (basically makes it so that you can't have touch of death combos)*""Undizzy"" system (basically makes it so that there can't be super long combos that build tons of meter)*combos aren't hard to do, and they aren't restricted to, this character can only do this combo, there's tons of combos that you can do.*super fun even when you're losing(just opinion like this entire review)*2d bewbs....... what I'm just into that stuff.Cons*Difficult to get very good at even if you can do the tutorial mode*Very difficult to be competitively succesful with just one character, so you have to learn at least 2*In terms of player skill level, there's no middle ground, either you know what you're doing or you don't*Although the game isn't execution heavy, its still kind of difficult to do specific combos if you don't practice*Wait Fillia's not 18......... oh well at least we still have Parasoul.Quick overviewPersonally I love this game to death, it's one of the first fighting games I decided to competitively play(or at least try to). The gameplay is pretty fast, especially to the untrained eye. To people who are watching videos to find out whether or not they should buy this game, you might have noticed this, you might feel a bit like gohan when he's watching that one fight in dbz. The game by nature of air combos, IPS, and the ""undizzy"" system, is very reset heavy. To non fighting game players, what this means is that, this game is centered around getting a hit comboing, then perhaps setting up a situation where you can get another hit and continue comboing. Please note that there are no touch of death combos in this game. Learning to combo is probably more important in this game than in Street Fighter or BlazBlue. So for newer players this might be a bit of a turn off. But trust me, its pretty easy to learn combos. Thanks to the chain system, (basically, you can press lets say, light punch, medium punch, then hard punch and the attacks will ""auto combo"" or the more used term, ""chain"") the place where most newer fighting game players will probably be confused is when it comes to launching your opponent, but if you do the tutorial it shouldn't be a problem. Plus there are tons of basic combos online, just make sure that the version of the game in the video is up to date. Any way, onto some other stuff, so lets go over characters, this game is pretty diverse when it comes to characters, in terms of design and actual gameplay. To a newer player you might think that every character is rushdown and offensive based, with the exception of Peacock and maybe Parasoul. But actually its not really true. Every character can be played in many different ways, but there are optimal ways to play the character. The way you know what kind of character(rush down, grappler, etc.) you're playing, is how your character is supposed to play the neutral. For example, Peacock wants to play the neutral on the opposite side of the screen and chucking stuff at you at a distance, but for Fillia, she desperately wants to get into your face and just destory you, to do that she does a lot of dashing on the ground and lots of jumping HP because it has a huge hitbox. Or you have a character like Parasoul, she has good normals(a move that doesn't require a joystick motion), a projectile to use full screen, command normals for a threatening low high mixup, and a huge hitbox on Jumping HP, she's capable of playing a full screen neutral game, but also she can get in and rush people down. In terms of artstyle, stages, and aesthetic stuff, its really different, the artstyle is reminiscent of the batman the brave and the bold series, but still looks very unique. The backrounds are filled with funny references to other game series and FGC stuff too. Also the backrounds are animated as well, if you don't think your computer can handl it that's ok there's an option to turn that off in the options menu.ConclusionFor about 15 dollars, you get one of the smoothest, craziest and most of all funnest fighting games on the PC. It's practically a steal. But to be honest it's not really for casual players although the visuals are something to be impressed about, you shouldn't buy the game just for that. If you are looking for a place to start getting good a fighting games, I would recommend this game only if you're willing to put in time and effort. Otherwise Street Fighter is a very good place to start, but does not contain as indepth of a tutorial as Skullgirls does. For Hardcore Fighting game players, you might notice that this game is very similar to the Marvel Vs. Capcom series, which was the creator's intention. I would highly recommend this to competitive fighting game players, it relieves some execution issues(such as instant air dashing), and very technical stuff(such as frame data) that the Marvel series has issues with. I love this game to death, its freaking awesome, and now that they've announced cross play between PS3 and PS4 I think it's only a matter of time before we can get cross play onto PC."
