,Recommended,245170,17573621,"Posted: 16 August, 2015",all,Scuttles,"Skullgirls is one of the more unique games in the 2D fighter genre. It's a 6 button fighter, which allows for a bit more than your traditional 4 button fighter. The smaller roster is backed up by how much care is put into each character. A lot of fighters seem to churn out a ton of characters which don't have a whole lot to them. Each character in Skullgirls has a unique playstyle that revolves around a core concept. For example: Cerebella is all about grabs, Peacock is about spacing with projectiles and teleports, and Valentine is about rushdown with zone breakers and strong air maneuverability.The game's art is another thing to take into consideration. Skullgirls looks very unique with its hand drawn frames that are very atypical for the fighting genre. Many other fighters rely on pixel by pixel sprites, and newer ones are transitioning towards 3D models. Personally, I really prefer the drawn frames. Whether or not you buy into the sexualization is up to you though. The game features a mostly female roster with more than a bit of fan service. It's up to you whether this is a plus, something you'd just ignore, or something that'll turn you away.One more important thing is that the game does receive free updates with new characters and stages. If you do not download the new character within the first few months of it coming out, it will cost money, but if you are attentive, everything is free.As a whole, Skullgirls is a very nice entry level fighter with nice tutorials. The assets add to make it one of the best and most unique games of its genre. It lacks the difficulty that some KoF players desire, but is a very great and well balanced fighter."
