76561198137728235,Recommended,245170,12978586,"Posted: 16 November, 2014",all,Xedhadeaus,"Take some of the most classic impactful fighting games like Marvel vs Capcom 2 and King of fighters 2003 and Capcom vs. SNK 2 and squeeze the elements together in a tasty blend of did I just see panties, and you have skullgirls.It is a beautiful game to look at as well as play, and like some of the newer fighting games, there is more impact upon different specials and not just special strengths, so some moves have same inputs but different moves depending on strengths which is good, though if you were looking for a similar move with a smaller hole... You may miss out.Combat is incredibly smooth, the moves go together and supers are basic and practically impossible to accidentally do, which is phenominal for those ryu 3 super mistakes... you can easily switch outs and perform snap backs, as well as use the one character you excel at without having to carry around a bunch of mules to bide.However... Because it is a new game, I find myself slightly annoyed at the matchups, because like in marvel vs capcom 1 or xmen vs street fighter, there are chances you will have to face the same opponets again, so if you hate the seemingly dedicated projectile character, You will seemingly have to sit through the megaman and bass king missile boss again just to get through it... If you don't know what you're doing. So eventually when there are more characters to use. It will probably rival or beat the fighting games it is modelled after. Mechanically it may already have. But it surely will after they have enough legacy content to lay onto the game."
