,Recommended,245170,13011404,"Posted: 19 November, 2014",all,ラムブ,"From someone that never entirely liked fighting games. (This is the exception)Sure, I played Tekken when I was younger, but that was just a mass of button mashing and spamming. I heard about this game from the infamous Matt and Woolie (Who make a cameo in the game), as well as one of my friends mentioned that he played it a lot. I was also a bit reluctant to buy it when people said that it was one of the more difficult fighting games.I didn't know what to expect from this game really. I bought it since it was on sale, and heard a few good things about it, so I jumped and took the chance. I just thought it was some fighting game where you spam buttons or do combos or something... It's not that. Skullgirls has a pretty damn steep learning curve. Instantly tried playing Arcade on ""Normal"" and I was used to wipe the floor (sometimes literally). If you're somewhat new to fighting games like I was, do the Training levels more than once. Even on ""Easy"", a poor player will get nearly or completely destroyed. (Damn you Big Band) Since I'm only a few hours in, I've still got much to learn. But damn, this game is really addictive. Recently, the game hasn't left my mind. Getting a chain higher than 3 gives this sense of achievement. I really love and enjoy the art style; it has its own uniqueness to it.Some criticism: The campaigns could be more related to each other as well as a bit longer. Other than that, I've been having fun.Goodbye productivity! (Again...)"
