76561198053372965,Recommended,245170,32235719,Posted: 7 June,all,Deej,"I have been playing Skullgirls since release. Though my Steam playtime may say otherwise, I have been enjoying this game on console mostly, since I originally purchased it on my PS3. This game is a delight. A throwback and respectful nod to the 2D fighters of old, while managing to contain the ferocity of newer 2D fighter titles.I found out about the game when it was still in development, through a college friend who was doing clean-up animation on it at that time. One thing I will always remember, is the claims Mike Z and the animation team made about how the animation of the sprites would be top notch. They did not lie. This game holds some of the most beatiful HAND DRAWN animations you may see in a fighting game, or any other genre for that matter. I think it is obvious to understand that I believe this game to be artistically flawless.The cast of the game is, for lack of better word, amazing. The concepts for each fighter are well addressed and easily understood. Their designs are amazing and the lore that accompanies each individual is satisfying. Although many people were not happy with the inclusion of the male fighters, I welcomed the addition as a fresh breath to the game. I only wish there were more on the roster.Mechanically, this game hit the mark. Many patches plagued the release of it, but what shortly was given to us was a fighting game that in my opinion would be the most balanced fighter in the market. As I said before, the game is a nod to 2D fighters of old. This means many of the commands will be easy to figure out and complete. Thus, many critiziced the mechanics as ""already done"". I was quite happy with seeing mechanics as good as MvC2 tossed into a salad with the likes of mechanics like the ones in Guilty Gear X. Because the mechanics were so familiar, the game became one of the most user friendly fighters I have played. The tutorial is also very good. Only thing I kinda wish for was a bigger roster and a moveset list. But nothing that really hurts so far. Trust me. Playing the game before all the DLC characters were introduced was a deal of love for it.The lore in the game is amazing. Each character has an amazing story and frankly I want more. The writing was pretty darn good. The voice acting was on point and no character sounded like the last, for which I was very happy.Overall, the game is a must for any fighting game afficionado. No other fighting game currently has been as polished as this one. I bought it on the PSN and bought it on Steam. And if it meant ensuring this team of amazing developers got the recognition they need, I'd purchase it again.TL;DRGraphics: 10/10Gameplay: 9/10Replayability (Solo): 7/10Replayability (Multiplayer): 10/10Story: 10/10Most RecommendedP.S. Can't wait for LabZero to give us Indivisible."
